##DICTATION: a Sharp turn-like acceleration, they left | Wuhan Wuhan Wuhan

MICRO-SIGNAL ZGZS001

Introduction, Voice of China, latest news

"The time of a grain of Ash, falls on the individual head, is a mountain. " In the suddenly pressed pause key danger city Wuhan, both the individual is at a loss and helpless, also has the mortal to come forward. Panic, pain, sadness, emotion... disaster, hard people become soft.
We want to record the history of Wuhan in the Spring of 2020 through the narration of 10 people.

We want to record the history of Wuhan in the Spring of 2020 through the narration of 10 people.

I'm Claire Kuo, the reporter.

He was first noticed in a photograph of a lone figure on an empty platform, carrying a backpack, getting ready to board a train. You can't see his face because he's not looking back.

On Weibo, where the photo was posted, there were 1,950 comments and 44,000 likes. That's not a surprising number compared with the viral tweets that followed. It was published at 22:46 on January 23, and the text told people that he was the first medical expert from Shanghai to go to Wuhan on assignment from the National Health Commission, and had already arrived.

In a large number of medical teams to assist Wuhan before, the first departure of the lonely figure particularly impressed me. A full month later, I saw him in the South six ward of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. His name is Zhong Ming, deputy director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Fudan University. On the day of the interview, he wore a surgical cap and a surgical mask that hid his good looks; but after a steady tone, I felt his professionalism, his rationality, his rigor, his delicacy, his warmth.

1

One phone call and we're off

My name is Zhong Ming, from Shanghai Fudan University affiliated Zhongshan Hospital, is a doctor in the Department of Critical Care Medicine.

On the morning of January 23, as the deputy director of our department responsible for medical treatment, I joined several other hospitals in Shanghai in a video teleconference with the health commission. Around 10:30, I received a call from President Qiu Haibo. Qiu, who is a member of the high level Expert Group of the Peking Union Medical College Hospital, said he was already in Wuhan with Professor Du Bin, Director of the ICU.

President Qiu told me, need to transfer a few people come over, ask me to be willing to go? I mean, yeah, definitely.

Back then, I knew as much about the epidemic as anyone, and I read about it on the Internet. If there's one thing you know a little bit more about, it's through in-house hospital meetings and teleconferences. I guess I knew it was bad, it was a lot of patients, it was a human-to-human thing.

I went back to the office to pick up some things, did some work, and then I went home to pack.

The kid saw me coming home from work, and he was like, "what are you doing here, Dad? "? I said I was going on a business trip. She said, "you won't go to Wuhan? " I said I really go to Wuhan, also told her to obey. She said nothing on the surface. Our family's disposition is all like this, "the love in the heart mouth difficult to open" that.

I had a lunch at home and had a simple talk with my wife and daughter. My wife's a doctor. She's used to it. Originally, this Spring Festival, we are ready to go to Australia for tourism, six months before the trip was set. I want to take advantage of the new year to relax a little time, to accompany them to play. I was in America for two years, and I didn't spend much time with them.

I simply packed up my clothes and luggage. The Chairman of the Labor Union, the Deputy Director of the party office and the medical director of our hospital came to see me off. They also urgently bought me some daily necessities. Then they took me to the high-speed railway station and set off.

I was the only one transferred to Shanghai that day. I can't get in. I have to get to Macheng first. There wasn't a lot of people on that train.

A car picked me up in Macheng, dropped me off at the entrance to the Wuhan Expressway, and replaced me here with a car capable of entering downtown Wuhan. At that time, unlike the later majority of troops, they can charter a plane directly "airdrop" to Wuhan.

2

To the highest level of combat

I'm from Jiangxi. I came to Wuhan when I was in college. My wife is in Wuhan University, Tongji Medical University, so I have a kind of Wuhan.

The impression of Wuhan is a very big city, a lot of delicious. Because hot, and like to eat spicy, we are generous character, the voice is also big. Environment is good, Wuhan University has Cherry Blossoms, the Yangtze River, Han River, very beautiful.

Traffic in Wuhan was bad before, but this time it was surprisingly quiet. There were no cars, no people on the road. As someone once said, the city was hit the pause button, and all of a sudden it froze, it froze.

The next day, New Year's Eve. We'll be at the gold and Silver Lake in the morning. It was drizzling. When the car pulled into the hospital, there seemed to be no one there at all, which was quite the atmosphere I had imagined.

President Qiu took us directly to the south seventh floor of the ICU, is the original hospital ICU. Put layers of clothing on the door and went in. Sense control expert Li 600 million teacher is also here, she has been emphasizing the sense control protection thing with us. At the time, it felt like it was really serious, like the contagion might be unknown.

When we went in there, we saw a lot of very sick people and very busy nurses and staff wearing positive pressure helmets with fresh air systems. Just walked into the ward to see a patient, next to the patient was brought in, the medical staff very busy in preparing beds, bed, adjust various equipment, breathing machine, ECMO. I felt like I was going straight into a state of battle at the highest level. I was nervous.

I am engaged in the serious medicine, each kind of big emergency scene, the high pressure scene has experienced, this is my coming to the gold and silver lake significance. But first aid is usually given in the face of a known disease, even if it is severe. But that scene in the money pit, is unknown, I am infectious to the virus, its occurrence rule, is unknown.

3

It's so hard... all the work is so hard

In the first echelon to Wuhan, there are four members of the Expert Group of the National Health Commission. In addition to me, there is Professor Sang Ling of the Guangzhou Medical University, who is a student of Academician Zhong Nanshan; Professor Zheng Xia of the First Affiliated Hospital of Zhejiang University, which is also the hospital of Academician Li Lanjuan, there is a very rich experience in dealing with the epidemic; Another is the northern Jiangsu People's Hospital ICU director Professor Zheng Ruiqiang, he is President Qiu Haibo's students, who participated in the SARS.

At that time, Professor Zheng Ruiqiang went to Wuhan Lung Hospital, the three of US stayed in the Golden Pool to work. Professors Sang Ling and Zheng Xia left me in the ICU on the seventh floor and put me on the sixth floor.

The sixth floor is the ICU, which was converted from the TB Ward. The staff, including hardware and software, are not the configuration of the ICU. They said it was more challenging, so I came to the sixth floor. I have been working on the sixth floor.

For a long time, the beds were very tight, and there were too many patients coming in to be admitted. There were about 30 beds on each floor, and there was a time when we kept patients in 22 to 24, because we wanted to improve the quality of care, so we kept the beds relatively under control, so that we could do the job a little bit more delicately, no, I'm tired of it.

But it's hard. The first thing is the hardware.

The ICU requires a certain amount of bed spacing, because our operation will be at the head of the bed, on both sides of the bed, and probably anywhere. But the sixth floor of this ward was originally a general ward, so do a lot of things very cramped, to move the bed to move around, very troublesome.

Normal ICU has a crane tower, a lot of pipelines, lines are placed on the crane tower, it is easy to move. But this place doesn't have one, just a bedside table, and a patient with only one oxygen port, no Compressed air port. Not even a lot of high-end surveillance equipment. We can only rely on those simple monitoring means to speculate, may have what kind of pathological changes.

There's also the matter of manpower.

A typical ICU bed requires 2.5 to 3 nurses, and even with 25 beds, a ward requires at least 60 to 75 nurses. But at the time, we had about thirty nurses, and half of them had no ICU background.

Professional sensitivity, responsiveness, and proficiency can determine a lot of things. There's a big difference between a nurse with a non-ICU background and a nurse with an ICU background, because any patient here, is the most serious patient we've ever had in our original job, and patients come up with all sorts of things, and without an ICU background, you didn't have time to react. You didn't have the ability.

Because of the isolation ward, our information exchange is also very difficult, so many people's information, all rely on a walkie-talkie.

Usually I want to know something about a patient, so I can always go to the bedside. But we can't now. We have to go through the intercom. The patient's not fine. It's GonNa take us 15,20 minutes to get dressed in there, and a lot can happen in the meantime. You don't know what's going on with a patient if you don't have an understanding or proficiency with the team; when you get there, the time window passes; and then you're in there trying to do something, and I don't have a very skilled nurse to work with you, which makes all the work very difficult.

4

Under heavy protective gear,

All the senses are diminished

Although I am an expert in critical care medicine, treating infectious diseases is not my area of expertise. When I first got here, it took me a long time to go through all the protective gear before I went into the room, and I didn't know if it was a good thing or not, even with the supervising teacher around.

According to the standard, we have to wear two layers of gloves, if the ward operation, wear three layers. With each layer of clothing, flexibility is greatly affected. For some operations, such as touching an artery, after wearing two or three layers of gloves, the sensitivity of the sense of touch will drop a lot. There was a lot of control involved, but I was wearing very thick gloves and clothes, and the precision of my movements was greatly affected.

Plus, it's not a standard I.C.U. , it's a regular ward, like it was a long time ago, the lights are regular fluorescent lights, it's very dark, the goggles are foggy, it's hard to see, it's hard to hear. The whole feeling is that all the senses are diminished.

The suits are heavy and breathless, often soaking wet and physically challenging.

At the time of SARS in 2003, there were only eight patients in Shanghai, and it wasn't my turn to go to the front line. I experienced the 2008 earthquake in Wenchuan County when I was parachuted into Sanjiang, a village near Yingxiu, Wenchuan County, by helicopter.

Earthquakes and epidemics, though both sudden and catastrophic, can feel very different. Wenchuan County earthquake, the risk is mainly in aftershocks. We ended up sleeping in tents, in open spaces, where the risk was less and you could sleep through the night as long as you could.

Unlike this new coronavirus, we don't know how it spreads, so I don't know what kind of protection is effective. Does it work when I'm at work? Is it working for me in the living quarters? It's not really bottoming out. It might be safe, it might not be safe. We're in a state of uncertainty.

We don't know what kind of weapon we can use against an enemy like this.

5

A sharp turn of acceleration,

They... left

Looking back at my previous work, I can not guarantee that many critically ill patients will be rescued, but I am able to predict the course of the disease in most cases.

But in the land of gold and silver, a lot of patients leave unexpectedly.

There was a female patient, not very old, maybe fifty. I've always had a lot of faith in her, and one day I even told her, if you get any better, I'm GONNA have to transfer you out of here, so you have to have faith. Then one day, her oxygenation deteriorated so rapidly that she couldn't think straight, she had to be intubated; after intubation, with our intensive treatment, she was stable for a while, but one day at noon, she suddenly, he's oxygenating again. His vitals are dropping. He's not getting up. Soon the heart stopped. It was so fast, the CPR wasn't working.

Really, the very vivid images of what I was talking to her, which are still in my head, hit me very hard. I'm sure a lot of doctors have experienced that.

Patients, no matter how old they are, often start out with mild symptoms, some don't even have symptoms, some just have a fever and cough that slowly progresses to shortness of breath, but when you use the inhalation intervention, for example, high-flow oxygen inhalation, or breathing machine non-invasive support, the patient can enter a stable state. When we first saw these patients, we thought they were stable.

However, once the disease has entered its accelerated phase, which we observe is usually about three weeks after onset, it can quickly progress into rapid deterioration, requiring tracheal intubation, invasive suction, and even an ECMO. Even with this intensive support, breathing is very poor, and many patients go into circulatory failure, shock, kidney failure, or myocardial damage.

It may take a day or two, or even a day, from the patient's poor acceleration to the time of death.

A sharp turn-like acceleration, and soon left, fast enough to let us all a bit stunned, a bit unprepared.

The patients are dying to live, and they know we're here for medical help, so they're grateful. Those words of gratitude, I am very impressed, can not help but think a lot.

If you think about it a lot, and you're always in a certain amount of tension, you won't sleep as deeply as you do at home.

This is reality. I'm here. I'm dealing with it as best I can. Occasionally, during breaks, he would talk to his wife about medical matters, but mostly about life. We all hope that a brief conversation each day will be a way to relax, talk about things in life, and make each other feel safe.

Each Other feel that the other is well, is we can rest assured that the premise of the work.

6

A month later, I was like a war veteran

After a month here, I think I've learned something about regularity, like being a war veteran.

From the initial understanding of the situation, to the initial recognition of the challenge is very big, and then to experience the challenge, there are good times and bad times, and now, slowly feel some regularity, mentality slowly adapt, also become more calm.

It's hard not to get a little carried away. Sometimes in the ward to see patients in bad condition, instinct will be anxious. But to be honest, it wasn't as demanding or urgent as it was at my old hospital. Because in a familiar and energetic environment, everyone has the responsibility to do a better job; but in the Golden Pool, everyone is already working as hard as they can, putting in 200 percent of their effort, not 100 percent, so you can't make unrealistic demands.

My colleagues here in Wuhan entered the fight against the epidemic a month or more earlier than I did. Themselves, their families, their lives, have been seriously affected by the epidemic. But these Wuhan colleagues around me, almost no one said "I can't" , "I want to take a step back" , no. Every day they do their own thing in silence, do not negotiate with you, you want me to do what I do. Many Times these colleagues are my role models and my motivation to keep going.

There were a lot of other medical teams coming in, and everyone was in a good mood. We know we're having a hard time, but people still make jokes when they're together. We're all in the same trenches, and there's a sense of optimism in the trenches, and it's not every day we're all together complaining.

And very well adapted to life. I always joked that the Marriott we stayed at had achieved communism ahead of time. There is no money for lodging or meals, and supplies are piled up at the door, ready to be picked up when you need them.

7

It's like a park in here

We've also learned a lot about process and experience since we arrived.

The process is much more efficient. From where a patient comes in, where he should be put in bed, who should be in charge, what tests the nurse should do, what tests we should do up here, what tests we should do next should be done every couple of hours, we all make decisions based on the individual patient.

We don't want to overtest ourselves, because in a situation where nurses are so scarce, the nursing workforce is absolutely guaranteed, but we don't want to give up any chance of treatment for really critical patients, we should check. We have to check.

Including the timing of the intubation. When we first got here, a lot of the patients were relatively late to intubate, and as long as we had enough oxygen, we thought it was okay. And then we found that, a lot of the time, even with enough oxygen, if the patient is still in a very difficult state, his lungs will continue to deteriorate, so I'm going to block it much earlier, use the invasive aspirator as a protective ventilation strategy to avoid further lung deterioration.

Now we can tell the difference: If the patient is young and there is hope, we will intervene early. We also concluded that older patients, especially older men, or patients with hypertension, diabetes, or chronic kidney disease, have a lower survival rate. Aggressive treatment can put a strain on circulation and heart function, and many times he may not be able to handle it. With these patients, we maintain a relatively conservative approach. These improvements are based on the accumulation of experience, and are slowly summed up on the basis of previous experience in the struggle.

In the early days, the most serious patients in the city were concentrated in the Jinyintan hospital and the Wuhan Lung Hospital. We Fed back the work experience and clinical data from these hospitals to the health and Health Commission, the HHS will adjust the rescue methods based on our work. For example, in the beginning, a local medical team was usually a mixture of several hospitals into a medical team, and now it has basically become a unit to receive the organizational system. We Zhongshan Hospital has a team of more than one hundred and thirty people, the entire system received the Wuhan University two wards, are his colleagues, are very familiar with the people, cooperation will be more tacit.

Now, the burden of the Golden Pool Hospital is also much lighter. The vast majority of patients are admitted and the proportion of critical cases is greatly reduced. In addition, those large-scale, organizational, strong medical institutions came, they share a large number of critically ill patients.

One of the most typical examples is director Chen, who is in charge of receiving patients in Jinyin Tan. At first, he kept answering the telephone every day, saying, "we must have a patient" and "we must have an extra bed. " Now there are fewer and fewer such calls, even when we have a spare bed.

Golden Lake is the best Chinese hospital I have ever visited. From the sixth floor where I work, there are a lot of big, dense trees. Every day on the way to work can see a lot of birds, such as magpies. I've never seen a hospital with such good ecology. A Walk in the hospital is like a walk in the park. But behind it all, in every building, there are a lot of patients, a lot of hard-working medical staff.

My daughter is 13 years old this year, she is very happy, because the beginning of school has finally postponed, her dream has finally come true. Now that she's taking online classes, she has a new problem: she has to punch a clock every day because her homework is back.

It was a special experience in a special situation, and I believe she will never forget it.
